<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Rsa on Aurora</title><link>https://notes.yoooo.fun/tags/rsa/</link><description>Recent content in Rsa on Aurora</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 06 Jan 2024 22:21:46 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://notes.yoooo.fun/tags/rsa/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Create Self-signed Certificate with custom subject</title><link>https://notes.yoooo.fun/posts/self-signed-cert/</link><pubDate>Fri, 10 Mar 2023 17:33:32 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://notes.yoooo.fun/posts/self-signed-cert/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="self-signed-certificate">Self-signed Certificate
&lt;/h1>&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>The deprecated, legacy behavior of treating the &lt;code>CommonName&lt;/code> field on X.509 certificates as a host name when no Subject Alternative Names are
present is now disabled by default. It can be temporarily re-enabled by adding the value &lt;code>x509ignoreCN=0&lt;/code> to the &lt;code>GODEBUG&lt;/code> environment variable.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Note that if the &lt;code>CommonName&lt;/code> is an invalid host name, it&amp;rsquo;s always ignored, regardless of &lt;code>GODEBUG&lt;/code> settings. Invalid names include those with any
characters other than letters, digits, hyphens and underscores, and those with empty labels or trailing dots.&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
